node.text:
Lock & Co. Hatters in London has been designing and selling high quality hats since 1676. It has served celebrities and royalty throughout history, withstood a bombing in WWII, and now survived the Covid-19 pandemic which was the first time in history it had to close its doors.

#HatMaking #lockandcohatters #London #StillStanding #Businesses

node.title: How the World’s Oldest Hat Shop Has Stayed in Business for Nearly 350 Years

node.text:
Saied Hussain has been hand making tiles out of cement for over 50 years. He says he’s one of the last still doing this work in Egypt — most other workshops couldn't withstand competition from marble and ceramic tiles. We went to Cairo to see how his business is still standing.

#StillStanding #Egypt #CementTile #MarbleTile #BusinessInsider #Tradition

node.title: How one man in Egypt is keeping this 200-year-old tile tradition alive

node.text:
Bananas are facing a pandemic, too. Almost all of the bananas exported globally are just one variety called the Cavendish. 

The Cavendish is vulnerable to a fungus called Panama Disease, which is ravaging banana farms across the globe. If it's not stopped, the Cavendish may go extinct. 

We visited a farm in Colombia infected with Panama Disease and a lab in the Netherlands studying the fungus to see if biosecurity and breeding can save the $25 billion banana industry.

node.title: Why The World’s Most Popular Banana May Go Extinct

node.text:
Before they officially become Air Assault-qualified, all soldiers must graduate from a physically and mentally challenging course known as the Army’s "10 toughest days." Chief video correspondent Graham Flanagan spent four days inside The Sabalauski Air Assault School in the Fort Campbell Army Installation on the Tennessee-Kentucky border. According to the Army, Air Assault operations involve missions requiring the insertion and evacuation of personnel and equipment using assault helicopters.

The training is divided into three phases: combat assault, sling-load operations, and rappelling. But before phase one begins, all students must survive "day zero," which culminates with an obstacle course featuring two major events that all students must conquer — otherwise they are dropped from training before phase one begins.

node.title: How soldiers are trained in a course known as the Army's "10 toughest days"

node.text:
High-quality leather is synonymous with Italian fashion. Some of the most expensive leather is made through a process called vegetable tanning. It's a craft that has its origins in prehistory, and today the technique is kept alive in Tuscany. This time-consuming process can take weeks to produce a type of leather that becomes especially beautiful with age, all thanks to the use of naturally occurring vegetable tannins. While this method for making leather may be threatened by the world of fast fashion, its makers remain hopeful that genuine craftsmanship never goes out of style.

node.text:
Victoria’s Secret is doing a major rebrand, but former execs and senior-level employees have told Insider they pushed for these changes for years.

The new changes aim to make the brand more inclusive, and has most notably seen the removal of the famous Angels and runway shows. But former employees said ex-CEO Les Wexner shut down suggestions to kill the brand’s annual fashion show and give it a new voice, telling them "I am the only one in this room who really understands what women want."

Insiders say Victoria’s Secret also refused to start a sports bra line. "They weren’t interested because it wasn’t pushing your boobs up to create cleavage," one insider said. "To them, sweat is only sexy when you’re having sex."

For the full story, click the link in our bio. 

Story by Mary Hanbury.

[Credit: AP Photo/Mary Altaffer, Evan Agostini/Invision/AP, Business Insider/Mary Hanbury]

node.text:
If you've been priced out of buying a home, there aren't many places to hide. The red-hot rental market is getting increasingly expensive as well.

Rental prices for single-family homes shot up 6.6% between May 2020 and May 2021, vastly higher than the 1.7% year-over-year increase the year before, according to property data firm CoreLogic.

The new data from CoreLogic reinforces the trend of single-family house rents skyrocketing across the country. According to Insider's Taylor Borden, the reshuffling of people moving during and after the pandemic has helped fuel a rental boom in places like Phoenix, while people are returning to hard-hit cities like New York and San Francisco, driving up rents nationwide.

Click the link in our bio to read the full story by Andy Kiersz.

(Credit: Shutterstock, CoreLogic Single-Family Rent Index)

Anyone working a public-facing job might expect to encounter some shocking moments, especially in the retail industry. That's especially true for Walmart's legion of nearly 1.6 million US store employees, who work at the largest retail chain in the world.

Insider spoke to six workers — four currently employed by Walmart and two who recently worked there — about the most shocking aspects of their jobs. We confirmed the employment status of every employee cited in this story. Several workers interviewed asked to remain anonymous for fear of retribution.

Read the full story at the link in our bio.

(Credit: Getty Images)

The employees said they' watched customers snack on grapes, apples and other produce items before paying. INSIDER'.

Photo by Business Insider on July 20, 2021.
